	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_917159">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_917159">That was an interesting, thought provoking post.<br />
<br />
As I was reading it, let me share what was going through my mind:<br />
<br />
I think that besides the comradery of friendships and the experience advancement of characters, one of the most key motivations for people is loot, frankly.  That is why I believe hardly anyone really bothers spending much time in old, low level zones.  With the ridiculously high statistical gear that can be bazaar purchased now, it seems much more common for people to simply super-twink a new character with bazaar gear and then power-level them through the old content as rapidly as possible while barely even catching the names of the mobs and zones.<br />
<br />
My first thought for a possible solution to this is to update alot of the loot tables for the newbie zones.  Place some more competitive drops on Named mobs to entice people to actually crawl and explore and encounter the old content in hopes of acquiring loot that isn't pathetically inferior to cheap bazaar items.<br />
<br />
Of course the next thought that entered my mind was, if the loot was modified enough to make this work then you would find people simply bringing in their 2-box or 3-box level 70 alts to get these drops the easy way.<br />
<br />
Would it be unreasonable to suggest placing a level cap on these old zones (or new lowbie instances?) with revamped loot tables, similar to what was done with the Naggy / Vox encounters?<br />
<br />
I guess what I would propose as a possible solution is to revamp loot tables for many of the low level zones with significantly higher statistics and focus effects.  Heck, perhaps even place level CAPS on gear items making them unusable after a certain level, requiring people to continually re-gear themselves with low level content like those who had to do that when the game was new.  --And bar many of these zones (or possibly just mobs?) from high level characters coming in and trivializing the content and farming it.<br />
<br />
/shrugs<br />
<br />
<img src="images/smilies/smile.gif" border="0" alt="" title="Smilie" class="inlineimg" /></div>
