		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_917332">Definitely a post to make you think, Claud.<br />
<br />
One thing I disagree with a little, at least lately in my experience, is that EQ is main-centric.  Course, I'm just going by guildies and friends on Emarr, but over the past few months more and more people are dragging out their alts.  <br />
<br />
Why?  Boredom, for one.  I want to progress, not kite another goddamn 69.1.  And if no one's on working on stuff I am, like ToB access, I'll log to an alt.  Or if its my day off and early, and there's 8 people on in my guild, I'll log to an alt.<br />
<br />
Second, an alt opens up my grouping potential.  My 2nd character was an SK, got him to 53, stripped him for cash and retired him.  Guess what?  I played him as a shroud until I could regear him, then worked my skills, did some MM, worked my skills more, and got him to 70.  So now, if I can't get a group with Laed, but someone says &quot;any tanks lfg?&quot;...get my point?<br />
<br />
But you are otherwise on the mark about the low-end game.  There are plenty of alts out there, but they're still just on a mad dash to 70.  And points by other people: too many zones, not enough toons, people clustering to the fastest xp, and pitiful loot tables in the old world when so many have the plat to blow on infinitely better...are all well said.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
