	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_918189">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_918189">Very nice post. There is no question that players face an uphill struggle finding groups to level lower level characters. I also agree whole-heartedly with the point that a lack of low level play is EQs #1 problem and recognize its long term detrimental impact on the game. However, although I hesitate to disagree with Claud in a public forum after watching him shred others with his verbal acumen, I do not see a practical solution. <br />
<br />
I believe that the core of the issue that prevents new players from achieving that &quot;stratified tier&quot; is simultaneously what I love about EQ and what frustrates me about EQ. That is the fact <b>EQ is DIFFICULT!</b> It is challenging, time consuming, requires patience, and forces you to arrange your schedule to coincide with the schedule of roughly 50 other people possibly scattered all over the globe in order to progress close enough to even glimpse the top tier.<br />
<br />
The answer is not to make things easier at the lower levels. Claud's argument there is sound. Nerkahia's post is the best solution I have heard to date because loot is a driving force for almost all of us and is tied intimately to advancement in EQ, but Zruu's one liner regarding AAs forces me to confront the reality of the EQ game mechanics and recognize the inherent problem. New content and nice loot would provide an incentive of sorts initially, but when faced with the daunting task of taking an alt up through the levels <i>and</i> earning the AA's to make the character truly viable, the required time commitment limits the effectiveness of such measures.<br />
<br />
The question I thought about as I read the thread is even though I recognize the problem, given the blood, sweat, and tears I put into developing my main what incentive could SOE offer to make significant play time with an alt or lower level character attractive? Although I have started several alts in the past, they quickly lose their appeal for me. My fundamental problem with playing alts is that even if the loot/xp/new content is sufficient motivation in and of itself for playing the lower level character(s), faced with a choice of how to spend limited EQ playtime I cannot justify sacrificing the time I would otherwise pour into my main to further his advancement. In short, EQs appeal for me is tied into the well-named culture of the main.<br />
<br />
At this point I am not sure that there is anything the developers can do to change the difficulty, and consequently the time required, for advancement without altering the core of the game. Also, I believe such changes would likely result in more harm than good. While I would like to see an increase in the amount of low level play, I am not willing to devote a couple of years to raise another character to the level of my main. I would bow to the demands of work, family, and other outside issues and go the route of so many others to another game or pastime. <br />
<br />
So, given I would never devote the time to develop an alt to that higher tier where he can even glimpse the top end content, could I be content playing an alt at lower levels knowing his progress will eventually stagnate? Honestly I do not see what incentive would suffice. Kiting 69.1 again is not particularly exciting, but the AA's I get from doing so add to my main's overall development and (hopefully) in the long run allow the ability to pursue other objectives. It is not the short term gain that keeps me interested in EQ; it is the focus on the long term development of my main.<br />
<br />
And so the circle returns to Claud's starting point. It is almost impossible for new characters to function viably at low levels given the games current state because EQ is designed with the concept of playing in a group fundamental to its dynamics and most players are focused on their high level mains. A player focuses on his or her main because the time and effort required to develop a character to that level requires a large commitment to the character. The commitment and persistence result in a sense of achievement as the character advances. The sense of achievement reinforces the desire to play the main. Ease of advancement, be it PLing, twinking, or purchasing pre-loaded characters, does not offer the same sense of achievement and results in overall decreased commitment that I believe carries over to EQ as a whole, not just to individual characters. In fact making advancement easier, whether through more powerful loot or increased low-level experience, would not only result shrinking the 1-60 world but in the long run would decrease the commitment of the new player resulting in these players actually leaving EQ more quickly than they would without these incentives. While EQ might attract more players in the short run, the bulk would not be long term subscribers.<br />
<br />
Having said that, I recognize no one in this thread proposed diluting EQs current level of difficulty. The question is how do the designers reinvigorate the typical players desire to play low level characters at least part of the time? Adding new low level content or reinvigorating the old content to make it more challenging, intriguing, and dynamic sounds like a good start. Adding desirable loot that cannot be farmed by high level characters for their twinks is an appealing component as well. But in the end I do not feel the combination of these factors would inspire me and others like me to leave our mains in favor of an alt, at least not in the numbers required to create a viable low level character base where new players could find enough groups that they could progress sufficiently and maintain their interest.</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
