	<td class="alt1" id="td_post_918273">
	
		
		<!-- message -->
		<div id="post_message_918273">Sadly, one of the highest motivators for playing ower levels toons was removed from implementation due to player dissatisfaction: The 'Trivial Loot code'.  If there were items that were only available from &quot;lower level&quot; content which were needed as spell components, or for tradeskills, or for quests, etc. then there would be a greater <i>need</i> for lower level characters.<br />
<br />
EQ has great replayability but as Claude noted in his first post it has been around so long that much of the playerbase is focusing on higher level content.  There is simply far more incentive to fully develop one <i>main</i> character than there is to start multiple &quot;new&quot; characters.<br />
<br />
Unless they make rewards (exclusively) available to lower level characters which are attractive to higher level characters, the problem will persist.<br />
<br />
Another option, similar to the Shroud mechanism available currently, is to allow higher level characters the ability (through quest or whatever) to effectively lower their level temporarilly - but maintain their class, race, factions, etc.  This would be a difficult coding job but I think it would be far more effective at motivating players to play lower level content than Shrouds are.  It would be much more enjoyable to play my actual Wizard character, with his old lower level gear equipped, then it is to play some Goblin or Evil Eye Wizard which has a completely different set of spells, stats, and skills.<br />
<br />
Hell, the plane of Time was breached long ago by mortals ...there is a perfect explanation for the sudden appearance of the same character in the gameworld within a variable level range.<br />
<br />
P.S. imagine how much fun it could be to twink your own (lower level) &quot;main&quot;!  /snicker</div>
		<!-- / message -->
	
		
		
		
		
		
	
	</td>
</tr>
<tr>
	<td class="alt2">
